# Phase 6 — Install Capacitor

Install Capacitor early so your application is mobile-ready from the beginning.

```bash
npm install @capacitor/core
npm install -D @capacitor/cli
npm install @capacitor/android
```

Initialize Capacitor.

```bash
npx cap init
```

Example:

```text
App Name:
MyApp

App ID:
com.example.myapp
```

Create the Android project.

```bash
npx cap add android
```

---

# Phase 7 — Configure Capacitor

Edit `capacitor.config.ts`

```ts
import { CapacitorConfig } from "@capacitor/cli";

const config: CapacitorConfig = {
  appId: "com.example.myapp",
  appName: "MyApp",
  webDir: "out",
};

export default config;
```

---

# Phase 8 — Configure Next.js (Static Export Only)

If your application is intended to run entirely as a static site inside Capacitor, update `next.config.ts`:

```ts
import type { NextConfig } from "next";

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  output: "export",
  trailingSlash: true,
  images: {
    unoptimized: true,
  },
};

export default nextConfig;
```

> **Important:** If your application uses Server-Side Rendering (SSR), Server Actions, or other server-only Next.js features, keep the default Next.js configuration instead of enabling `output: "export"`.

